<CaseStudy
  period="2022–23"
  tag="Enterprise Analytics"
  title="Later 360 — One Data Model for Every Enterprise Client"
  metrics={[
    { value: "60%+", label: "Reduction in ad hoc SQL tickets" },
    { value: "5", label: "Enterprise clients on shared infrastructure" },
    { value: "4 wk", label: "Investment to eliminate per-client SQL debt" },
    { value: "0", label: "Net-new SQL written per client, post-migration" },
  ]}
  honestBlock={{
    variant: "grey",
    label: "THE THING I'D UNDO",
    body: "I waited until client five to make the platform case. At clients one and two, bespoke SQL was the right call — the pattern wasn't established, custom builds shipped faster. By client three, the maintenance cost was visible. I didn't make the investment proposal until client five. That gap created four clients of migration overhead and weeks of fragile SQL I then had to defend in incident reviews. The decision to build the unified layer was right. Making it later than I should have is the thing I'd undo.",
  }}
  pills={["dbt", "BigQuery", "GCP", "SQL", "Python", "Affiliate Analytics", "Enterprise Analytics"]}
  current="work"
>
  <p>
    Enterprise analytics at Later meant serving five high-value clients — each $1M+ ARR — with
    dashboards across affiliate, paid, and organic channels. The early approach was pragmatic:
    write bespoke SQL per client, ship fast, move on. Three clients in, it was working. It was
    also quietly breaking. Every new client multiplied the maintenance surface: custom query logic
    per source, no shared models, upstream schema changes silently breaking one client's report
    without touching another's. Service desk tickets for ad hoc SQL fixes were the leading
    indicator that the architecture was wrong.
  </p>
  <p>
    The case to leadership was straightforward but uncomfortable: stop shipping the next client
    until we build the platform that ships all future clients faster. A four-week investment to
    normalize cross-source data into a unified dbt modelling layer — affiliate, paid, organic —
    in exchange for zero net-new SQL written per client from that point forward. Leadership
    pushed back. The preference was to keep shipping. The counter was explicit: every new client
    on bespoke SQL adds maintenance surface that compounds. A four-week investment now versus
    accumulating weeks of fragile maintenance per future client is not a close call.
  </p>
  <p>
    The unified dbt layer shipped. All five enterprise clients onboarded on shared infrastructure.
    Service desk ticket volume for ad hoc SQL fixes dropped 60%+ against the pre-migration
    baseline. New clients onboard on the same models — no net-new SQL written per client from
    client four onward. The schema normalization across affiliate, paid, and organic sources was
    the hard technical problem. Convincing leadership to pause delivery to make it happen was harder.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
